Shared Qs (018)


  1. Question

    A geometric sequence has a first term 0.7 and a common ratio 1.1. Find the sum of the first 21 terms.

    The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).

    (We call the sum of a geometric sequence a geometric series.)


    Solution

    It might be helpful to reference geometric series. Identify the parameters.

    \[a = 0.7\]

    \[r = 1.1\]

    Define the explicit formula to find the \(n\)th term.

    \[a_n = (0.7)(1.1)^{(n-1)}\]

    The sum of the first 21 terms could be donated with \(S_{21}\) or with the upper-case Sigma summation operator.

    \[S_{21} = \sum_{i=1}^{21}(0.7)(1.1)^{(i-1)} \]

    A constant factor (multiplier) can be brought in front of a summation operator.

    \[S_{21} = 0.7\sum_{i=1}^{21}(1.1)^{(i-1)} \]

    Just to be clear, we are attempting to find the following sum:

    \[S_{21} = (0.7)\left(1+1.1+1.1^2+1.1^3+\ldots+1.1^{17}+1.1^{18}+1.1^{19}+1.1^{20}\right) \]

    If you are cool, you might multiply both sides by 1.1, and distribute to all the terms in the summation.

    \[1.1\cdot S_{21} = (0.7)\left(1.1+1.1^2+1.1^3+1.1^4+\ldots+1.1^{18}+1.1^{19}+1.1^{20}+1.1^{21}\right) \]

    Subtract the previous two equations and simplify by eliminating the opposite terms.

    \[S_{21} - 1.1\cdot S_{21} = (0.7)(1-1.1^{21})\]

    Factor out \(S_{21}\) from the terms on the left side of the equation.

    \[S_{21}(1-1.1)= (0.7)(1-1.1^{21})\]

    Divide both sides by \((1-1.1)\).

    \[S_{21}= \frac{(0.7)(1-1.1^{21})}{(1-1.1)}\]

    This process suggests the geometric series formula.

    \[S_n = \frac{a(1-r^n)}{1-r} \]

    \[S_{21}= 44.8017496\]

  11. Question

    An infinite geometric series converges if and only if \(|r|<1\). A convergent series will approach a finite value as more terms are added; a divergent series will approach infinity. Is the following geometric series convergent?

    \[60~-~48~+~38.4~-~\ldots\]


    1. Yes, the series converges.
    2. No, the series diverges.

    Solution

    Determine the common ratio by dividing the second term by the first term.

    \[r = \frac{-48}{60} = -0.8\]

    Notice, this is the same as the ratio of the third and second terms.

    \[r ~=~ \frac{38.4}{-48} ~=~ -0.8\]

    Determine the absolute value of the common ratio.

    \[|r| ~=~ |-0.8| ~=~ 0.8\]

    Compare the absolute common ratio to 1. If it is less than 1, the series converges; otherwise, the series diverges.

    \[|-0.8| < 1\]

    So, the series converges.

    Compare the absolute common ratio to 1. If it is less than 1, the series converges; otherwise, the series diverges.

    \[|-1.08| > 1\]

    So, the series diverges.



  18. Question

    An infinite geometric series converges if and only if \(|r|<1\). A convergent series will approach a finite value as more terms are added; a divergent series will approach infinity. Is the following geometric series convergent?

    \[-70~+~83.3~-~99.127~+~\ldots\]


    1. Yes, the series converges.
    2. No, the series diverges.

    Solution

    \[r = \frac{83.3}{-70} = -1.19\]

    \[r ~=~ \frac{-99.127}{83.3} ~=~ -1.19\]

    Determine the absolute value of the common ratio.

    \[|r| ~=~ |-1.19| ~=~ 1.19\]

    Compare the absolute common ratio to 1. If it is less than 1, the series converges; otherwise, the series diverges.

    \[|-1.19| > 1\]

    So, the series diverges.

  21. Question

    A convergent infinite geometric series has a finite sum. First, remember the geometric series formula:

    \[S_n = \frac{a(1-r^n)}{1-r} \]

    If \(|r|<1\), then \(\lim\limits_{n\to\infty}1-r^n = 1\), because repeated multiplication of a proper fraction creates numbers closer and closer to 0.

    So, if \(|r|<1\), then

    \[S_{\infty} ~=~ \frac{a}{1-r} \]

    Find the sum of the following geometric series (with infinitely many terms).

    \[-800~+~720~-~648~+~\ldots\]


    Solution

    Determine the common ratio by dividing the second term by the first term.

    \[r = \frac{720}{-800} = -0.9\]

    Notice, this is the same as the ratio of the third and second terms.

    \[r ~=~ \frac{-648}{720} ~=~ -0.9\]

    Determine the absolute value of the common ratio.

    \[|r| ~=~ |-0.9| ~=~ 0.9\]

    Because \(|r|<1\), the series is convergent.

    \[a = -800\] \[r = -0.9\]

    \[S_{\infty} ~=~ \frac{a}{1-r} ~=~ \frac{-800}{1-(-0.9)} ~=~ -421.0526316\]

  31. Question


    The fractal above is composed of many line segments. The largest segment is 1 unit long. There are then 3 segments, each with a length of \(k = 0.31\). To continue the pattern, there are 9 segments with length \(k^2=0.0961\). Then, 27 segments with length \(k^3\) and 81 with length \(k^4\) etc…

    How much total length is needed to construct this fractal (with infinite depths of recursion)? Find the sum of all the lengths.

    In other words, if \(k=0.31\), evaluate the following:

    \[\sum_{i=0}^\infty(3k)^{i} ~=~ 1 + 3k + 9k^2 + 27k^3 + \ldots ~=~ ~? \]

    The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    This summation is a geometric series. In general, if \(|r|<1\) then

    \[a + ar + ar^2 +ar^3 + ar^4 +\ldots + ar^{\infty} ~=~ \frac{a}{1-r} \]

    In our case, \(a=1\) and \(r=0.93\). Notice, to calculate the common ratio \(r\), we multiply the branching number (3) by the scaling factor (\(k=0.31\)).

    \[\frac{1}{1-0.93} = 14.2857143\]

    So, the total length of all the segments is 14.2857143 units.

    So, the total length of all the segments is 12.5 units.



  41. Question


    The fractal above is composed of many line segments. The largest 4 segments are each 1 unit long. There are then 16 segments, each with a length of \(k = 0.26\). To continue the pattern, there are 64 segments with length \(k^2=0.0676\). Then, 256 segments with length \(k^3\) and 1024 with length \(k^4\) etc…

    Is the sum of the lengths finite or infinite?


    1. Finite
    2. Infinite

    Solution

    This summation is a geometric series. In general, if \(|r|<1\) then

    \[a + ar + ar^2 +ar^3 + ar^4 +\ldots + ar^{\infty} ~=~ \frac{a}{1-r} \]

    In our case, \(a=4\) and \(r=1.04\). Notice, to calculate the common ratio \(r\), we multiply the branching number (4) by the scaling factor (\(k=0.26\)).

    Because \(|r| > 1\), the sum is infinite

  51. Question


    A fractal is generated such that the biggest circle has an area of 1 square units. The next generation has 4 circles, each with an area of \(k=0.12\) square units. In the next generation of 16 circles, each has an area of \(k^2=0.0144\), then 64 circles with area \(k^3\) each, etc…

    Find the area of the fractal. The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    We find the common ratio \(r = (4)(0.12) = 0.48\).

    \[1 + 0.48 + 0.48^2 + 0.48^3 + \ldots ~=~ \frac{1}{1-0.48} ~=~ 1.9230769\]
